@node Main "Appendix 5: Print Header & Footer Tokens..."
@toc "FinalCalc:guide/main.guide/Main"
@font topaz.font 8
Print Headers and Footers accept special tokens in their text.  All tokens
start with a '%' character, then another character which defines the special
text to insert, and optionally more optional control over the token surrounded
by double-quotes.


The following is a list of those tokens:

@{u}Token     @{uu}  @{u}Description                                                @{uu}
%p          The current page number being printed
%p"12"      The current page number, plus a number
%P          The total number of pages in the current print job
%P"12"      The total number of pages, plus a number
%d          The current date, formatted with the global date format
%t          The current time, formatted with the global time format 
%D"format"  The current date, formatted with a custom date format
%T"format"  The current time, formatted with a custom time format
%f          The file name of the current project
%F          The full path name of the current project
%cA1        Contents of a cell.
%c"range"   Contents of the top-left cell in a range.
%l          The sheet user title
%j          The Print Job's name.
%r          The current page number in roman numerals.
%R          The total pages in roman numerals.
%z          Custom Page Numbering token.  (see below for details)
%%          Output a % sign


@{u}Example              @{uu}   @{u}Result                                         @{uu}
Page %p of %P           Page 1 of 15
Page %p"12"             Page 13
%d                      21 Jan 1993
%t                      11:15:00
%D"Wwww, d Mmmm yyyy"   Monday, 21 January 1993
%t"hh:mm aa"            11:15 a.m.
%f                      test.sheet
%F                      work:sheets/test.sheet
%cA1                    <contents of cell A1>
%c"TEST"                <contents of top left cell in range TEST>




@{b}@{u}Header/Footer Custom Page Numbering Token:@{ub}@{uu}

The %z token in print headers/footers allows you flexibility in defining how
the page number is to be printed.  The token takes a string in double-quotes
which defines the output page number.  It accepts 5 types of 'page number
tokens'.

   Token   Number Printed            Definition of Number Printed
  -------  -----------------------   ------------------------------------------
     P     current page              current page + starting page
     L     current local page        current page only
     W     current page wide         current page across width
     H     current page high         current page across height + starting page
     G     current local page high   current page across height
  <other>                            copy character to output


Each of those tokens default to showing the number in decimal notation.  An
optional modifier can be added after the token to define how the number is
printed:


  @{u}Modifier@{uu}    @{u}Format                 @{uu}   @{u}Result                   @{uu}
   <none>     Decimals                  1, 2, 3
      a       Alphabetic (lower case)   a, b, c, ..., aa, ab, etc.
      A       Alphabetic (upper case)   A, B, C, ..., AA, AB, etc.
      r       Roman (lower case)        i, ii, iii
      R       Roman (upper case)        I, II, III


Examples:
  
      @{u}Header/Footer         @{uu}      @{u}Result              @{uu}
      Page: %z"p"                 Page: 1
      Page: %z"hga"               Page: 3a
      Page: %z"hgA"               Page: 3A
      Section %z"pR"              Section III
      Chapter %z"pR" Page: %p     Chapter III, Page 5


  There is a lot of interaction between the token type, the page count
  increment type and the page count step.  This allows you many different
  possibilities, but can also be confusing.



@{b}@{u}Print Job Header/Footer Text requester:@{ub}@{uu}

The Print Job Header/Footer Text requester comes when when you click on a [?]
gadget attached to a string gadget that expects a Print Job header or footer.

The requester shows you a list of the tokens you can use and what each does.
It allows you to select and paste the tokens right into the string, while
showing you 'live' what the resulting header/footer string will look like.
@endnode
